, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston Richard, Westmorland, England":"Preston Richard, Westmorland, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1331–1368":"1331–1368","1360–1415":"1360–1415","1305–1332":"1305–1332","1304–1363":"1304–1363","about 1360":"about 1360","1363":"1363","1360":"1360","1305":"1305","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","Abt 1360":"about 1360","1368":"1368","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1331":"1331","16 June 1363":"16 June 1363","Hempnall, Norfolk, England":"Hempnall, Norfolk, England","Pennington, Lancashire, England":"Pennington, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Preston Richard, Westmorland, England":"Preston Richard, Westmorland, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pennington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire and Cumbria):","habitational name from Pennington in Furness (Lancashire), which derives from Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, or from Pennington in Leigh (Lancashire), which probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Pinna</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","habitational name from Pennington (Hampshire), or from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hampshire); see   Penton  . All have the same etymology as Pennington in Furness; see 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Penington","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Pennington  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: Edward Penington, born in 1667 in Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England, was appointed surveyor-general of the province of PA in 1698 and accompanied William Penn to Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Penton","meanings":["English (mainly Hampshire):","habitational name from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hanmpshire), or from a shortened form of   Pennington   2. The placenames denoted a farm or estate for which a penny tax was payable (Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i>).","in north-west England, a shortened form of   Pennington   1, from either of the places called Pennington in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":6,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Pennington was born in 1331, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Pennington, was 26 and his mother, Joan Multon, was 28. He married Elizabeth Malton about 1360. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1368, in Lancashire, England, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1331–1368":"1331–1368","1360–1415":"1360–1415","1305–1332":"1305–1332","1304–1363